<subSubSection id="AC8E4B8151A618CBFF5EFF7EEE8E1E25" pageId="157" pageNumber="158" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="E42B180A51A618CBFF5EFF7EEBBE1D21" blockId="157.[151,1437,152,611]" pageId="157" pageNumber="158">
<emphasis id="D6E0C41851A618CBFF5EFF7EEE0C1CBC" bold="true" box="[199,308,225,251]" pageId="157" pageNumber="158">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="800565FB51A618CBFEDBFF7FED6F1CBC" author="Kawashima" box="[322,599,224,251]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Kawashima" pageId="157" pageNumber="158" pagination="241 - 261" refId="ref118611" refString="Kawashima, I., Suzuki, H. &amp; Sato, M. (2003) A Check-List of Japanese Fireflies (Coleoptera, Lampyridae and Rhagophthalmidae). Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology, 9 (2), 241 - 261." type="journal article" year="2003">
Kawashima 
<emphasis id="D6E0C41851A618CBFE54FF7EEEC61CBD" box="[461,510,224,250]" italics="true" pageId="157" pageNumber="158">et al</emphasis>
. (2003)
</bibRefCitation>
ably overviewed the confusion relating to the identification and misidentifications of this species and presented a colour picture of the 
<typeStatus id="3B2FA6A851A618CBFCDEFE9BEC911D59" box="[839,937,260,286]" pageId="157" pageNumber="158">holotype</typeStatus>
female. Despite the name they considered it was not from 
<collectingCountry id="9C83589A51A618CBFEA8FEB6EE491D04" box="[305,369,297,323]" name="Japan" pageId="157" pageNumber="158">Japan</collectingCountry>
and probably had never been. It is impossible to identify the type female as it belongs to a wide range of S. E. Asian species which have a pale yellowish dorsum with black tipped elytra.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E42B180A51A618CBFF5EFEEFEE8E1E25" blockId="157.[151,1437,152,611]" pageId="157" pageNumber="158">
The single male from 
<collectingCountry id="9C83589A51A618CBFE59FEEEED381DCC" box="[448,512,369,395]" name="Japan" pageId="157" pageNumber="158">Japan</collectingCountry>
in NHML was not dissected but appears to be an 
<taxonomicName id="2394638951A618CBFBABFEEFEB881DCD" authorityName="Ballantyne Lambkin &amp; Fu" authorityYear="2013" box="[1074,1200,368,394]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Abscondita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="157" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D6E0C41851A618CBFBABFEEFEB881DCD" box="[1074,1200,368,394]" italics="true" pageId="157" pageNumber="158">Abscondita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. and has pale yellow abdominal tergites, and pale yellow ventrites anterior to the LOs. This would suggest 
<taxonomicName id="2394638951A618CBFB35FE0BEAAD1DE9" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1858" box="[1196,1429,404,430]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Abscondita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="157" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perplexa">
<emphasis id="D6E0C41851A618CBFB35FE0BEAAD1DE9" box="[1196,1429,404,430]" italics="true" pageId="157" pageNumber="158">Abscondita perplexa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However it presents a second problem. We are assuming that the Thunberg specimen was mislabelled and actually is not from 
<collectingCountry id="9C83589A51A618CBFE85FE42EE641DB0" box="[284,348,477,503]" name="Japan" pageId="157" pageNumber="158">Japan</collectingCountry>
but from some other S. E. Asian country where Thunberg travelled. Short of suggesting that the species once existed in 
<collectingCountry id="9C83589A51A618CBFE05FD9EEEE41E5C" box="[412,476,513,539]" name="Japan" pageId="157" pageNumber="158">Japan</collectingCountry>
and has since become extinct, the more likely explanation is that these two specimens were actually mislabelled. 
<collectingCountry id="9C83589A51A618CBFE26FDBAEEC71E78" box="[447,511,549,575]" name="Japan" pageId="157" pageNumber="158">Japan</collectingCountry>
reveres its firefly population and it is almost impossible to conceive that the species has gone unnoticed there.
</paragraph>
